---
import PageShell from '../../../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'overview', text: 'Overview', level: 2 },
  { id: 'healthcare-system', text: 'Healthcare System', level: 2 },
  { id: 'visa-requirements', text: 'Visa Options', level: 2 },
  { id: 'insurance-requirements', text: 'Insurance Requirements', level: 2 },
  { id: 'recommended-providers', text: 'Recommended Providers', level: 2 },
  { id: 'costs', text: 'Expected Costs', level: 2 },
  { id: 'scenarios', text: 'Real-World Scenarios', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Greece Insurance Guide', href: '/countries/greece/insurance' },
  { title: 'Insurance for Seniors', href: '/insurance-for/seniors' },
  { title: 'Greece Golden Visa', href: '/visas/investor-visa/in/greece' },
  { title: 'Insurance with Pre-existing Conditions', href: '/insurance-for/pre-existing-conditions' },
  { title: 'Portugal for Seniors', href: '/insurance-for/seniors/in/portugal' },
];

const providerColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'entryAge', header: 'Max Entry Age' },
  { key: 'renewal', header: 'Renewal' },
  { key: 'monthlyFrom', header: 'From (65-69)' },
  { key: 'greeceFit', header: 'Greece Fit' },
];

const providerRows = [
  { provider: 'Cigna Global', entryAge: '74', renewal: 'Lifetime', monthlyFrom: '$420-580/mo', greeceFit: 'Excellent' },
  { provider: 'Allianz Care', entryAge: '74', renewal: 'Lifetime', monthlyFrom: '$380-520/mo', greeceFit: 'Excellent' },
  { provider: 'BUPA Global', entryAge: '79', renewal: 'Lifetime', monthlyFrom: '$480-680/mo', greeceFit: 'Very Good' },
  { provider: 'AXA Global', entryAge: '74', renewal: 'Lifetime', monthlyFrom: '$400-560/mo', greeceFit: 'Very Good' },
  { provider: 'Interamerican (Local)', entryAge: '65', renewal: '75', monthlyFrom: '€120-280/mo', greeceFit: 'Good (Local)' },
];

const costColumns = [
  { key: 'category', header: 'Expense' },
  { key: 'monthly', header: 'Monthly' },
  { key: 'annual', header: 'Annual' },
];

const costRows = [
  { category: 'International Insurance (65-69)', monthly: '$400-580', annual: '$4,800-6,960' },
  { category: 'International Insurance (70-74)', monthly: '$550-800', annual: '$6,600-9,600' },
  { category: 'International Insurance (75-79)', monthly: '$750-1,100', annual: '$9,000-13,200' },
  { category: 'Greek Private Insurance', monthly: '€100-300', annual: '€1,200-3,600' },
  { category: 'Public System (with residency)', monthly: '€0', annual: 'Free with AMKA' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Health Insurance for Seniors in Greece | Retirement Guide"
  description="Guide to health insurance for seniors retiring in Greece. Golden Visa, public healthcare access, island living, and coverage options for expats 70+."
  headline="Health Insurance for Seniors in Greece"
  subheadline="Greece offers affordable Mediterranean living with access to public healthcare—but seniors need to understand the system before making the move."
  heroImage="/images/countries/greece-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Compare Senior Plans →"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna-global"
>
  <h2 id="overview">Why Seniors Choose Greece</h2>
  <p>
    Greece has emerged as an increasingly popular retirement destination, offering a unique combination of ancient culture, Mediterranean climate, island lifestyle options, and significantly lower living costs than Western Europe. For seniors, the ability to access public healthcare after establishing residency adds financial appeal.
  </p>

  <p>
    Popular retirement areas include the islands (Crete, Corfu, Rhodes), the Peloponnese peninsula, and areas around Athens for those wanting urban amenities. The Greek Golden Visa program, with its relatively low investment threshold, has attracted retirees looking to establish EU residency.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Key Facts for Seniors</h3>
    <ul class="text-primary-800 space-y-2">
      <li><strong>Healthcare system:</strong> Universal public system (ESY) available to residents</li>
      <li><strong>Quality:</strong> Good in major cities; variable on islands</li>
      <li><strong>English availability:</strong> Good in Athens and tourist areas; limited elsewhere</li>
      <li><strong>Climate:</strong> Mediterranean; hot summers, mild winters</li>
      <li><strong>Cost of living:</strong> 40-50% lower than UK/Northern Europe</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h2 id="healthcare-system">Greece's Healthcare System</h2>
  <p>
    Greece operates the National Health System (ESY - Εθνικό Σύστημα Υγείας), which provides universal coverage to all legal residents. For seniors, this is significant: once you have residency and an AMKA number (social security), you can access public healthcare essentially for free.
  </p>

  <h3>Public Healthcare (ESY)</h3>
  <p>
    The public system covers hospital care, specialist consultations, and subsidized medications. Quality varies significantly by location:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Athens and Thessaloniki:</strong> Major public hospitals with modern facilities</li>
    <li><strong>Regional cities:</strong> Generally adequate public hospitals</li>
    <li><strong>Islands:</strong> Basic health centers; serious cases transferred to mainland</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Wait times for non-urgent specialist appointments can be long (weeks to months), and navigating the system often requires Greek language skills or a local helper. Many seniors use public care for routine needs while maintaining private insurance for faster access and emergencies.
  </p>

  <h3>Private Healthcare</h3>
  <p>
    Greece has quality private hospitals, particularly in Athens. Facilities like Hygeia, Metropolitan Hospital, and Iatriko Kentro offer modern care with English-speaking staff. Costs are significantly lower than Western Europe or the US:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>GP consultation:</strong> €30-60 private</li>
    <li><strong>Specialist consultation:</strong> €50-100</li>
    <li><strong>Basic surgery:</strong> €3,000-8,000</li>
    <li><strong>MRI scan:</strong> €200-400</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-3">Island Living Consideration</h3>
    <p class="text-amber-800">
      If you're planning to retire on a Greek island, healthcare access becomes critical. Smaller islands have only basic health centers—serious conditions require ferry or air transfer to Athens. International insurance with evacuation coverage is essential for island retirees.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="visa-requirements">Visa Options for Senior Retirees</h2>
  <p>
    Non-EU seniors have several paths to Greek residency, with the Golden Visa being the most popular for those with investment capacity.
  </p>

  <h3>Greek Golden Visa</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Investment:</strong> €250,000-500,000 in real estate (varies by region)</li>
    <li><strong>Health insurance:</strong> Required for application</li>
    <li><strong>Duration:</strong> 5 years, renewable</li>
    <li><strong>Residence requirement:</strong> None (can live elsewhere)</li>
    <li><strong>Benefits:</strong> Schengen travel, path to permanent residency</li>
    <li><strong>Healthcare:</strong> Eligible for AMKA and public system access</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Financially Independent Person Visa</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Income:</strong> Sufficient passive income (no set minimum, typically €2,000+/month)</li>
    <li><strong>Health insurance:</strong> Required</li>
    <li><strong>Duration:</strong> 2 years initially, renewable</li>
    <li><strong>Residence requirement:</strong> Must actually live in Greece</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>EU/UK Citizens</h3>
  <p>
    EU citizens can move freely to Greece. UK citizens post-Brexit need to apply for residency but face minimal financial requirements. EU citizens with S1 forms from their home country can access Greek public healthcare immediately.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Need Insurance for Greek Residency?"
    description="Find coverage that meets Golden Visa or residency requirements."
    buttonText="Compare Plans →"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <h2 id="insurance-requirements">Insurance Requirements for Seniors</h2>
  <p>
    Greece requires health insurance for most visa applications, though requirements are less specific than some EU countries.
  </p>

  <h3>Golden Visa Insurance Requirements</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Valid health insurance covering Greece</li>
    <li>Coverage for medical and hospital expenses</li>
    <li>No specific minimum coverage stated (comprehensive coverage recommended)</li>
    <li>International or Greek insurance accepted</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>After Obtaining AMKA</h3>
  <p>
    Once you have Greek residency and obtain your AMKA (social security number), you're entitled to public healthcare. This typically takes 2-4 months after arrival. At this point, you can:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Use public healthcare for routine and hospital care</li>
    <li>Maintain international insurance for supplementary coverage</li>
    <li>Switch to a high-deductible plan for emergencies and travel</li>
    <li>Keep evacuation coverage, especially if living on islands</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Recommended Approach for Seniors</h3>
  <p>
    Start with comprehensive international insurance for the visa application and initial period. Once AMKA is established, evaluate whether to maintain full coverage or transition to a hybrid approach using public healthcare for basics and private insurance for complex or urgent needs.
  </p>

  <h2 id="recommended-providers">Recommended Providers for Greece</h2>
  <p>
    These insurers work well for seniors retiring in Greece:
  </p>

  <div class="my-8 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <ComparisonTable columns={providerColumns} rows={providerRows} />
  </div>

  <h3>Cigna Global</h3>
  <p>
    Excellent option for comprehensive coverage with strong European networks. Direct billing at major Greek private hospitals. Entry up to 74 with lifetime renewal. Good customer service in English.
  </p>

  <h3>Allianz Care</h3>
  <p>
    Offers both moratorium and full medical underwriting—moratorium is helpful for seniors with pre-existing conditions. Competitive pricing and good Greek network. Particularly popular with European expats.
  </p>

  <h3>BUPA Global</h3>
  <p>
    Accepts applicants up to 79—the highest entry age among major insurers. Premium pricing but comprehensive coverage and worldwide service. Essential option for seniors 75-79.
  </p>

  <h3>Greek Local Insurance</h3>
  <p>
    Local insurers like Interamerican, Ethniki, and Eurolife offer private health insurance at lower costs. However, age limits are typically strict (60-65 for new policies), coverage may be limited, and English support varies. Best as supplementary coverage or for younger retirees.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Compare Senior-Friendly Plans"
    description="Find coverage that balances cost and comprehensive protection."
    buttonText="See Options →"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
  />

  <h2 id="costs">Expected Insurance Costs</h2>
  <p>
    Insurance costs for seniors in Greece depend on the coverage type:
  </p>

  <div class="my-8 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <ComparisonTable columns={costColumns} rows={costRows} />
  </div>

  <h3>Cost Advantages in Greece</h3>
  <p>
    Greece offers significant cost advantages for senior healthcare:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Free public healthcare:</strong> Once you have AMKA, hospital care and medications are heavily subsidized</li>
    <li><strong>Affordable private care:</strong> Even without insurance, private care costs 40-60% less than Western Europe</li>
    <li><strong>Lower insurance premiums:</strong> "Europe only" coverage costs less than worldwide plans</li>
    <li><strong>EHIC access:</strong> Residents can get EHIC cards for travel within EU</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Cost-Saving Strategies</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Use public system:</strong> Access ESY for routine care and hospital stays</li>
    <li><strong>High-deductible plan:</strong> Keep international insurance for catastrophic coverage only</li>
    <li><strong>Europe-only coverage:</strong> Exclude worldwide/US coverage if you won't travel outside EU</li>
    <li><strong>Inpatient-only:</strong> Cover hospitalizations; pay outpatient costs yourself</li>
    <li><strong>Local + evacuation:</strong> Greek insurance plus standalone evacuation policy</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="scenarios">Real-World Scenarios</h2>

  <div class="grid gap-6 my-8">
    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 1: Routine Care with AMKA</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-3">Helen, 71, needs blood pressure medication in Crete.</p>
      <p class="text-green-700"><strong>Outcome:</strong> Visits local ESY health center with AMKA number. Sees doctor within a week. Pays €1 for prescription pickup. Uses public system regularly for chronic condition management.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 2: Private Specialist Access</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-3">Michael, 68, wants to see cardiologist quickly in Athens.</p>
      <p class="text-green-700"><strong>Outcome:</strong> ESY wait is 2 months. Uses Cigna Global to see private cardiologist at Hygeia Hospital within 1 week. €80 consultation covered after deductible.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 3: Island Emergency</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-3">Robert, 73, has chest pain on small Cycladic island.</p>
      <p class="text-amber-700"><strong>Outcome:</strong> Local health center stabilizes him. Air ambulance transfer to Athens arranged by BUPA Global—cost €15,000 covered. Treatment at Athens private hospital. Total claim: €32,000. This is why evacuation coverage matters for islands.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 4: Golden Visa Applicant</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-3">Sandra, 69, applying for Golden Visa from the US.</p>
      <p class="text-green-700"><strong>Outcome:</strong> Gets Allianz Care for application. Approved within 3 months. After moving, obtains AMKA and can access ESY. Keeps Allianz for private access and travel coverage.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 5: UK Retiree Post-Brexit</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-3">David, 70, British, retired to Greece before Brexit deadline.</p>
      <p class="text-green-700"><strong>Outcome:</strong> Maintained residency rights under Withdrawal Agreement. Has AMKA and uses public system. Also has S1 from UK covering healthcare costs. Keeps supplementary travel insurance for UK visits.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 6: Pre-existing Cancer History</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-3">Margaret, 72, cancer survivor 5 years clear.</p>
      <p class="text-amber-700"><strong>Outcome:</strong> Allianz Care moratorium underwriting excludes cancer for 2 years. She uses ESY for oncology follow-ups (excellent cancer centers in Athens) and Allianz for other conditions. After 2 years clear, Allianz covers cancer.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 id="faqs">Common Questions</h2>

  <div class="grid gap-6 my-8">
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I access Greek public healthcare?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-700">Yes, once you have legal residency and obtain an AMKA number (social security). This typically takes 2-4 months after establishing residency. EU citizens with S1 forms can access ESY immediately.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is the Golden Visa still available?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-700">Yes, though investment thresholds have increased in some areas (€500,000 in Athens, Thessaloniki, and popular islands; €250,000 in other regions). The program continues to attract retirees seeking EU residency and Schengen travel rights.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What about healthcare on the islands?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-700">Smaller islands have basic health centers only. Serious conditions require transfer to larger islands (Crete, Rhodes) or Athens. Evacuation coverage is essential. Larger islands like Crete have good hospitals (University Hospital of Heraklion).</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">I'm 76—what are my options?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-700">BUPA Global accepts applicants up to 79. Greek local insurers typically stop accepting new policyholders at 65. Once you have AMKA, public healthcare is available regardless of age. A combination of ESY access plus BUPA Global for emergencies and evacuation works well.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need to speak Greek?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-700">For private healthcare in Athens and tourist areas, English is common. For the public system and smaller towns, Greek is helpful. Consider hiring a translator or finding English-speaking doctors (many exist, especially those trained abroad).</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What about travel within Europe?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-700">As a Greek resident, you can obtain an EHIC (European Health Insurance Card) for emergency coverage in other EU/EEA countries. International insurance provides additional travel coverage. Schengen residency allows visa-free travel throughout the zone.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <CTABox
    title="Planning Your Greek Retirement?"
    description="Find insurance that covers your needs from visa application through settlement."
    buttonText="Compare Plans →"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6 mt-8">
    <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">
      <strong>Disclaimer:</strong> This guide is for informational purposes. Greek visa requirements, Golden Visa thresholds, and healthcare access rules change. Verify current requirements with Greek authorities and embassies. Consider consulting an immigration lawyer specializing in Greek residency and an insurance broker for personalized coverage advice.
    </p>
  </div>
</PageShell>
